<BODY>

<H2>Introduction to CS 39C</H2>

<H3>Getting to Know Each Other</H3>

<UL>
  <LI>Round table introductions
  <UL>
    <LI>What are your interests?
    <LI>Why are you interested in taking this course?
  </UL>
  <LI>(Electronic) photo taking and form filling
</UL>

<H3>Discussion Questions</H3>

<UL>
  <LI>Name a significant technological invention
  <UL>
    <LI>Why do you think that this invention is important?
    <LI>How might you quantify the importance of an invention?
    <LI>When do you think your significant invention actually took place?
    <LI>Do you know who was responsible for your invention?
  </UL>
  <LI>What words come to mind when you see the following names:
  <UL>
    <LI>Bill Gates
    <LI>Steve Jobs<BR>
    
    <LI>Thomas Edison
    <LI>Alexander Graham Bell<BR>
    
    <LI>George Lucas
    <LI>Ray Dolby
  </UL>
</UL>

<H3>What We Will Cover in this Course</H3>

<UL>
  <LI>The Ages of Technology (starting with the Industrial Age)
  <UL>
    <LI>1840-1860: Age of Steam
    <LI>1860-1880: Age of Rail
    <LI>1880-1900: Age of Invention
    <LI>1900-1920: Age of Electricity
    <LI>1920-1940: Age of Construction
    <LI>1940-1960: Nuclear Age
    <LI>1960-1980: Space Age
    <LI><B><I>1980-????: Information Age</I></B>
  </UL>
  <LI>The technological developments that underlie the Information Age: computers,
  communications, and their accelerating integration, from antiquity to the
  21st first century
  <LI>The societal, legal, regulatory, and economic implications of these
  technology developments
  <LI>Discussions, explanations, readings, projects, field trips
</UL>

<H3>What We Hope You Will Learn From This Seminar</H3>

<UL>
  <LI>Modern technological society is built on the efforts of many people:
  crackpots, visionaries, inventors, research and development teams, and
  entrepreneurs.
  <LI>Modern inventions are the culmination of technology developments that
  span decades or even centuries.
  <LI>New technologies continuously challenge society's economic and legal
  frameworks.
  <LI>Visionary individuals who come to control a technological industry,
  like Bill Gates, are not a recent phenomenon.
</UL>
</BODY>
